            "id": "f7934e62cd4e4036a6e8f",
            "questionText": "Astronomers are observing a distant galaxy using a powerful telescope array. X-rays emitted from a black hole are detected with a frequency of $!$3 \\times 10^{18}$!$ Hz. Given that all electromagnetic waves travel at $!$3 \\times 10^8$!$ m/s in a vacuum, calculate the wavelength of the detected X-rays in nanometers.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "783358162e1e40d1a3ed7",
                    "stepText": "Let's begin by identifying the equation that relates the speed of an electromagnetic wave to its frequency and wavelength. Please choose the correct formula from the options provided.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ac9e6112-e5e7-48ec-bb82-50fa7044d14a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{\\lambda}{f}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = f \\lambda$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{f}{\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\lambda - f$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "5fb97a81948a4f92a2fd4",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the correct relation, use it to calculate the wavelength in meters. Using $!$v = 3\\times10^8\\;m/s$!$ and $!$f = 3\\times10^{18}\\;Hz$!$, compute the wavelength by dividing the speed by the frequency. What is the wavelength in meters?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1e-10"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ac9e6112-e5e7-48ec-bb82-50fa7044d14a"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "9507e283fc51498898dab",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now convert the wavelength from meters to nanometers. Recall that $!$1\\;nm = 1\\times10^{-9}\\;m$!$. What is the wavelength in nanometers?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.1"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "nm",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ad755d70-94fb-44f0-8af1-57ca223ac8ac"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "36783a7f96e44e3e8e10e",
            "questionText": "Calculate the energy, in electronvolts, of a single ultraviolet photon with a wavelength of $!$300\\,\\text{nm}$!$. Use $!$h = 6.626 \\times 10^{-34}\\,\\text{J}\\cdot\\text{s}$!$ for Planck's constant, $!$c = 3.00 \\times 10^{8}\\,\\text{m/s}$!$ for the speed of light, and recall that $!$1\\,\\text{eV} = 1.602 \\times 10^{-19}\\,\\text{J}$!$.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "b2f82dbb53714e689c433",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the appropriate relation to calculate the energy of a photon. Select the formula that correctly relates the energy $!$E$!$, Planck's constant $!$h$!$, the speed of light $!$c$!$, and the wavelength $!$\\lambda$!$.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "ac9e6112-e5e7-48ec-bb82-50fa7044d14a"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E=\\frac{hc}{\\lambda}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E=h\\lambda c$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$E=\\frac{h}{\\lambda c}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "e75d464afa454b6680dc9",
                    "stepText": "Next, convert the given wavelength from nanometers to meters. Recall that $!$1\\,\\text{nm} = 10^{-9}\\,\\text{m}$!$. What is $!$300\\,\\text{nm}$!$ expressed in meters?",
                    "stepText2": "",
